## Data files

The image and label files are stored inside tar shards under:

```text
data/train/
data/val/
data/test/
```

Each tar file preserves YOLO-compatible internal paths, for example:

```text
images/train/example.jpg
labels/train/example.txt
```

## Integrity verification

The export includes:

- `checksums-sha256.txt` — SHA-256 hash of every shard and metadata/documentation
  file, for verifying nothing was corrupted or truncated after downloading.
- `manifest.csv` — one row per image, with its file paths, which shard it's packed
  into, individual image/label hashes, and object/class counts.
- `manifest-files-sha256.csv` — the same information as `manifest.csv`, flattened to
  one row per file (image and label as separate rows), the format used to verify
  hashes of individual files inside a shard.
- `validation_report.json` — result of validating the source YOLO labels before
  packaging (class ids in range, normalized coordinates, no orphan labels...). Issues
  found here would have already stopped the export, so a published copy always
  reports no errors.
- `verification_report_local.json` — result of re-verifying this very export right
  after it was built (global checksums recomputed, and every file inside every shard
  re-hashed against `manifest-files-sha256.csv`).

Use these files to verify downloaded shards and internal image/label hashes.

## Metadata files

Also included, useful for scripts and reproducibility rather than for training itself:

- `dataset_info.json` — machine-readable summary of the whole export: dataset
  name/slug/version, total image/label counts, the class map, and — per split —
  image/label/shard counts and the list of shard filenames.
- `metadata.csv` — a lighter version of `manifest.csv` without file sizes or hashes,
  meant for quick exploration (e.g. loading into pandas) without the extra columns.
- `HuggingFaceHub.yaml` — the resolved configuration this export was built from,
  read automatically by this project's own publishing tools. Not needed to use the
  dataset for training.

## Example extraction

From the directory containing the downloaded files:

```bash
mkdir -p extracted
cp donana.yaml extracted/

for f in data/train/*.tar data/val/*.tar data/test/*.tar; do
  tar -xf "$f" -C extracted/
done
```

Then train with a YOLO-compatible framework using:

```text
extracted/donana.yaml
```

